  "body": "On NixOS /lib/modules does not exist, it can instead be found at\r\n/run/current-system/kernel-modules/lib/modules where\r\n/run/current-system/kernel-modules is a symlink into /nix/store.\r\n\r\nThis pull request might be one way of solving the issue, I'm not entirely convinced this is the way to go however. Basically, what I'm trying to achieve with this is being able to specify an alternate location of the /lib/modules on host - on NixOS for example they can be found here:\r\n\r\n`/run/current-system/kernel-modules/lib/modules/`\r\n\r\nUnfortunately that's not the whole story because when you take a look inside that directory it looks like this:\r\n\r\n```sh\r\n~# ls -lah /run/current-system/kernel-modules/lib/modules/4.18.11/\r\ntotal 1.6M\r\ndr-xr-xr-x 2 root root   15 Jan  1  1970 .\r\ndr-xr-xr-x 3 root root    3 Jan  1  1970 ..\r\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root   98 Jan  1  1970 extra -> /nix/store/y45h3c82dqah71wnyapn50yhq6xkk265-zfs-kernel-0.8.0-rc1-4.18.11/lib/modules/4.18.11/extra\r\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root   84 Jan  1  1970 kernel -> /nix/store/k63w5zlz29xzrv40bv3fd7a13zwp7mwv-linux-4.18.11/lib/modules/4.18.11/kernel\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root 1.3M Jan  1  1970 modules.alias\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root 1.3M Jan  1  1970 modules.alias.bin\r\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root   93 Jan  1  1970 modules.builtin -> /nix/store/k63w5zlz29xzrv40bv3fd7a13zwp7mwv-linux-4.18.11/lib/modules/4.18.11/modules.builtin\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root 3.7K Jan  1  1970 modules.builtin.bin\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root 685K Jan  1  1970 modules.dep\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root 898K Jan  1  1970 modules.dep.bin\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root  472 Jan  1  1970 modules.devname\r\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root   91 Jan  1  1970 modules.order -> /nix/store/k63w5zlz29xzrv40bv3fd7a13zwp7mwv-linux-4.18.11/lib/modules/4.18.11/modules.order\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root  598 Jan  1  1970 modules.softdep\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root 590K Jan  1  1970 modules.symbols\r\n-r--r--r-- 1 root root 725K Jan  1  1970 modules.symbols.bin\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe problem with the above is that code here `pkg/util/sys/kmod.go` tries to cat the file `modules.builtin` which, as can be seen above, is actually a link elsewhere so that will fail and results in the agent CrashLooping even though you were able to specify an alternate /lib/modules host directory.\r\n\r\nI suppose that the module loading code (eg. calls to `modprobe`) would also fail because of the links above but we never get to that point.\r\n\r\nSo, I figured, if we were allowed to specify extra mounts we could mount the `/nix` directory inside the container in which case the links could be followed.\r\n\r\n<!-- Please take a look at our [Contributing](https://rook.io/docs/rook/master/development-flow.html)\r\ndocumentation before submitting a Pull Request!\r\nThank you for contributing to Rook! -->\r\n\r\n**Description of your changes:**\r\nAllows specifying an alternate lib/modules directory through environment variable.\r\nIt also allows specifying additional mounts through `AGENT_MOUNTS`.\r\n\r\n**Which issue is resolved by this Pull Request:**\r\nResolves #2189 \r\n\r\n**Checklist:**\r\n- [x] Documentation has been updated, if necessary.\r\n- [x] Pending release notes updated with breaking and/or notable changes, if necessary.\r\n- [x] Upgrade from previous release is tested and upgrade user guide is updated, if necessary.\r\n- [x] Code generation (`make codegen`) has been run to update object specifications, if necessary.\r\n- [x] Comments have been added or updated based on the standards set in [CONTRIBUTING.md](../blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#comments)\r\n",
